T1  - Envelope Theorems for Arbitrary Choice Sets
AU  - Milgrom, Paul
AU  - Segal, Ilya
Y1  - 2002/03/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00296
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 583
EP  - 601
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
KW  - envelope theorem
KW  - differentiable value function
KW  - sensitivity analysis
KW  - math programming
KW  - mechanism design
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00296
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The standard envelope theorems apply to choice sets with convex and topological structure, providing sufficient conditions for the value function to be differentiable in a parameter and characterizing its derivative. This paper studies optimization with arbitrary choice sets and shows that the traditional envelope formula holds at any differentiability point of the value function. We also provide conditions for the value function to be, variously, absolutely continuous, left- and right-differentiable, or fully differentiable. These results are applied to mechanism design, convex programming, continuous optimization problems, saddle-point problems, problems with parameterized constraints, and optimal stopping problems.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Measuring the Dynamic Efficiency Costs of Regulators' Preferences: Municipal Water Utilities in the Arid West
AU  - Timmins, Christopher
Y1  - 2002/03/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00297
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 603
EP  - 629
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
KW  - groundwater
KW  - dynamic program
KW  - nested fixed-point algorithm
KW  - publicly provided private goods
KW  - in situ shadow value
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00297
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Evidence suggests that municipal water utility administrators in the western US price water significantly below its marginal cost and, in so doing, inefficiently exploit aquifer stocks and induce social surplus losses. This paper empirically identifies the objective function of those managers, measures the deadweight losses resulting from their price-discounting decisions, and recovers the efficient water pricing policy function from counterfactual experiments. In doing so, the estimation uses a ?continuous-but-constrained- control? version of a nested fixed-point algorithm in order to measure the important intertemporal consequences of groundwater pricing decisions.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Quadratic Concavity and Determinacy of Equilibrium
AU  - Shannon, Chris
AU  - Zame, William R.
Y1  - 2002/03/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00298
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 631
EP  - 662
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
KW  - determinacy
KW  - infinite-dimensional commodity spaces
KW  - competitive equilibria
KW  - continuous-time finance
KW  - commodity differentiation
KW  - infinite horizon economies
KW  - Lipschitz economies
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00298
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - One of the central features of classical models of competitive markets is the generic determinacy of competitive equilibria. For smooth economies with a finite number of commodities and a finite number of consumers, almost all initial endowments admit only a finite number of competitive equilibria, and these equilibria vary (locally) smoothly with endowments; thus equilibrium comparative statics are locally determinate. This paper establishes parallel results for economies with finitely many consumers and infinitely many commodities. The most important new condition we introduce, quadratic concavity, rules out preferences in which goods are perfect substitutes globally, locally, or asymptotically. Our framework is sufficiently general to encompass many of the models that have proved important in the study of continuous-time trading in financial markets, trading over an infinite time horizon, and trading of finely differentiated commodities.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Shift Restrictions and Semiparametric Estimation in Ordered Response Models
AU  - Klein, Roger W.
AU  - Sherman, Robert P.
Y1  - 2002/03/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00299
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 663
EP  - 691
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
KW  - ordered response model
KW  - semiparametric estimation
KW  - shift restrictions
KW  - threshold points
KW  - survey data
KW  - transformation model
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00299
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We develop a √n-consistent and asymptotically normal estimator of the parameters (regression coefficients and threshold points) of a semiparametric ordered response model under the assumption of independence of errors and regressors. The independence assumption implies shift restrictions allowing identification of threshold points up to location and scale. The estimator is useful in various applications, particularly in new product demand forecasting from survey data subject to systematic misreporting. We apply the estimator to assess exaggeration bias in survey data on demand for a new telecommunications service.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Computing Normal Form Perfect Equilibria for Extensive Two-Person Games
AU  - Von Stengel, Bernhard
AU  - Van Den Elzen, Antoon
AU  - Talman, Dolf
Y1  - 2002/03/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00300
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 693
EP  - 715
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
KW  - extensive game
KW  - linear complementarity
KW  - Nash equilibrium
KW  - normal form perfect equilibrium
KW  - sequence form
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00300
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper presents an algorithm for computing an equilibrium of an extensive two-person game with perfect recall. The method is computationally efficient by virtue of using the sequence form, whose size is proportional to the size of the game tree. The equilibrium is traced on a piecewise linear path in the sequence form strategy space from an arbitrary starting vector. If the starting vector represents a pair of completely mixed strategies, then the equilibrium is normal form perfect. Computational experiments compare the sequence form and the reduced normal form, and show that only the sequence form is tractable for larger games.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Genuine Rank-Dependent Generalization of the Von Neumann-Morgenstern Expected Utility Theorem
AU  - Abdellaoui, Mohammed
Y1  - 2002/03/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00301
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 717
EP  - 736
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
KW  - probability weighting
KW  - expected utility
KW  - rank-dependent utility
KW  - probability trade-offs
KW  - probabilistic risk attitude
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00301
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper uses ?revealed probability trade-offs? to provide a natural foundation for probability weighting in the famous von Neumann and Morgenstern axiomatic set-up for expected utility. In particular, it shows that a rank-dependent preference functional is obtained in this set-up when the independence axiom is weakened to stochastic dominance and a probability trade-off consistency condition. In contrast with the existing axiomatizations of rank-dependent utility, the resulting axioms allow for complete flexibility regarding the outcome space. Consequently, a parameter-free test/elicitation of rank-dependent utility becomes possible. The probability-oriented approach of this paper also provides theoretical foundations for probabilistic attitudes towards risk. It is shown that the preference conditions that characterize the shape of the probability weighting function can be derived from simple probability trade-off conditions.
ER  - 

